    "## 3. Loading the Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Concepts\n",
    "\n",
    "**Rows and columns:** In a tabular dataset, each *row* represents one observation - here, one student. Each *column* represents one variable (feature or target) measured for that student. The intersection of a row and a column holds a single value.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Shape:** `df.shape` returns a tuple `(n_rows, n_columns)`. Understanding shape is the first sanity check after loading: it confirms the file was read completely and that no columns were merged or split incorrectly.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Structured data:** Structured data is organised into a predefined schema - fixed columns with defined types. It contrasts with unstructured data (free text, images, audio) and semi-structured data (JSON, XML). CSV files are the most common form of structured data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**If the file path is wrong:** Python raises `FileNotFoundError`. Always verify the path string, check for typos, and confirm the file exists at the specified location.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common CSV loading issues:**\n",
    "- *Encoding errors* - non-UTF-8 characters (e.g., accented names) require specifying `encoding='latin-1'` or `encoding='cp1252'`.\n",
    "- *Delimiter issues* - some CSV files use semicolons or tabs as separators; specify `sep=';'` or `sep='\\t'`.\n",
    "- *Header issues* - if the first row is not a header, pass `header=None` and assign `names=[...]`.\n",
    "- *Trailing whitespace* - column names may contain invisible spaces; use `df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()`."
   ]
