   "source": [
    "## 4. Initial Data Inspection\n",
    "\n",
    "### Data Types Explained\n",
    "\n",
    "| dtype | Meaning | Example |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| `int64` | 64-bit integer | age, exercise_frequency |\n",
    "| `float64` | 64-bit floating-point | study_hours, exam_score |\n",
    "| `object` | Python string / mixed | gender, diet_quality |\n",
    "| `bool` | Boolean True/False | rarely seen in CSVs |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why data types matter:** Machine-learning algorithms operate on numbers. If a numeric column is stored as `object` (string), arithmetic operations raise `TypeError`, statistical summaries are suppressed, and models refuse to train without preprocessing.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Numerical vs categorical variables:**  \n",
    "- *Numerical* - measured on a scale; arithmetic is meaningful (study hours, sleep hours).  \n",
    "- *Categorical (nominal)* - named groups with no natural order (gender, diet quality levels without ordering).  \n",
    "- *Categorical (ordinal)* - named groups with a meaningful order (parental education: High School < Bachelor < Master < PhD).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Continuous vs discrete:**  \n",
    "- *Continuous* - can take any value in an interval (exam score 0–100, sleep hours).  \n",
    "- *Discrete* - only specific values (exercise sessions per week: 0, 1, 2, …).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Impact on memory:** `float64` uses 8 bytes per value. A 1 000-row, 16-column float dataset uses ~128 KB. At scale (millions of rows), converting to `float32` or using categorical dtypes reduces memory by 50–75%."
   ]
