    "### 5.1 Missing Values\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is missing data?** Missing data occurs when no value is stored for an observation-variable combination. It can arise from survey non-response, sensor failure, data entry errors, or deliberate omission.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Three mechanisms of missingness:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Mechanism | Definition | Example |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **MCAR** (Missing Completely At Random) | Missingness is independent of both observed and unobserved data | Random system dropout |\n",
    "| **MAR** (Missing At Random) | Missingness depends on *observed* variables but not the missing value itself | Older students less likely to report parental education |\n",
    "| **MNAR** (Missing Not At Random) | Missingness depends on the *unobserved* value itself | Students with low mental health not reporting mental health score |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Bias from ignoring nulls:** Under MAR and MNAR, deleting rows with missing values (listwise deletion) introduces systematic bias — the remaining sample is no longer representative of the population.\n",
    "\n",
    "**How models behave with null values:** Scikit-learn raises `ValueError: Input contains NaN` for virtually all estimators. Models must receive complete data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why median is robust to outliers:** The median is the 50th percentile — it is insensitive to extreme values. If exam scores contain outliers at 0 or 100, the median is unaffected, whereas the mean is pulled toward those extremes. Imputing with the median preserves the central tendency without distortion."
   ]
