    "### 5.2 Duplicate Rows\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why duplicates cause bias:** A duplicate row means one student's data is counted twice (or more). This inflates the representation of that student's feature values, artificially narrowing variance and shifting means. In a 1 000-row dataset, even 50 duplicates can distort a regression slope meaningfully.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Real-world example:** In academic datasets, duplicates often arise from merging multiple administrative systems — the student information system and the learning management system may both export a record for the same student, and a sloppy join produces duplicates."
   ]
