    "### 5.3 Outlier Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is an outlier?** An outlier is an observation that lies at an abnormal distance from other values. It may represent genuine extremes (a student who studies 14 hours per day), measurement errors, or data entry mistakes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Effect on the mean:** The mean is the sum of all values divided by n. A single extreme value shifts the mean disproportionately. For example, if 9 students score 50 and one scores 150 (an error), the mean rises from 50 to 60 — a 20% distortion.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Effect on regression slope:** Linear regression minimises the sum of *squared* residuals. Outliers have large residuals, and squaring amplifies their influence. A single outlier can rotate the regression line by several degrees, completely changing the slope interpretation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**When to remove outliers:**  \n",
    "- When they are demonstrably erroneous (score > 100, negative hours).  \n",
    "- When the modelling goal is to predict *typical* students and outliers are truly anomalous.\n",
    "\n",
    "**When NOT to remove outliers:**  \n",
    "- When outliers are valid extreme cases (genius-level students *do* exist).  \n",
    "- When the model's purpose is anomaly detection itself.  \n",
    "- When the sample is small and removal would significantly reduce statistical power.\n",
    "\n",
    "**IQR Method:** Inter-Quartile Range = Q3 − Q1. Outliers are flagged beyond the fence `[Q1 − 1.5·IQR, Q3 + 1.5·IQR]`.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Z-Score Method:** A z-score measures how many standard deviations a value lies from the mean. Values with `|z| > 3` are conventionally considered outliers, assuming approximate normality."
   ]
  },
