    "## 6. Feature Engineering\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.1 Creating New Features\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is feature engineering?** Feature engineering is the process of using domain knowledge to create new input variables from existing raw data. It is often described as the most impactful step in the machine-learning pipeline — better features yield better models, regardless of algorithm choice.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why engineered features improve models:**  \n",
    "Models can only detect relationships that are represented in the feature space. If the true effect of \"screen time\" on performance depends on the *combined* hours of social media and Netflix, but these are only provided as two separate columns, a linear model may fail to capture the combined effect unless a sum feature is explicitly created.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Bias-variance tradeoff impact:** Adding well-designed features reduces bias (the model can capture more complex patterns). However, adding irrelevant features increases variance (the model overfits to noise). Feature engineering is an art that balances these two forces."
   ]
  },
