    "### 6.2 Encoding Categorical Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why ML models cannot read text:** Mathematical algorithms operate on numbers. A decision tree asks \"is value X < threshold T?\" — this question is meaningless for a string like \"Good\". Therefore, all categorical variables must be converted to a numerical representation before training.\n",
    "\n",
    "**One-Hot Encoding (OHE):** Creates one binary (0/1) column per category. If `diet_quality` has values {Poor, Fair, Good}, OHE creates `diet_quality_Poor`, `diet_quality_Fair`, `diet_quality_Good`. Used for *nominal* variables (no natural order).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Label Encoding:** Replaces each category with an integer (Poor→0, Fair→1, Good→2). Used for *ordinal* variables where the order is meaningful, or for tree-based models where ordinal integers are interpretable.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dummy Variable Trap:** When all OHE columns are included in a linear model, perfect multicollinearity arises (the columns sum to 1 identically). The fix is to drop one column (`drop_first=True`). Tree models are immune.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Curse of Dimensionality:** Encoding a categorical column with 100 unique values via OHE adds 99 binary columns. In high-dimensional spaces, data becomes sparse and distance-based algorithms (KNN, SVM) degrade rapidly.\n",
    "\n",
    "**When to use each:**\n",
    "- OHE: Linear models, logistic regression, nominal categories.\n",
    "- Label Encoding: Tree-based models, ordinal variables."
   ]
