    "### 6.3 Feature Scaling\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why scaling is necessary:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Many algorithms are sensitive to the magnitude of feature values:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Gradient-descent-based models** (linear regression, logistic regression, neural networks) — the gradient update step size is proportional to the feature value. Unscaled features cause some gradients to dominate, slowing or destabilising convergence.\n",
    "- **KNN** — distance is computed as Euclidean distance. A feature measured in hundreds (attendance_percentage: 0–100) dominates a feature measured in single digits (sleep_hours: 0–10), making the former disproportionately influential.\n",
    "- **SVM** — the margin depends on distance; unscaled features distort the optimal hyperplane.\n",
    "\n",
    "**StandardScaler:** Transforms each feature to mean=0, std=1: `z = (x − μ) / σ`. Preferred when the feature's distribution is approximately normal. Used in this project.\n",
    "\n",
    "**MinMaxScaler:** Transforms to [0, 1]: `x' = (x − min) / (max − min)`. Sensitive to outliers (a single extreme value compresses all other values toward 0). Preferred for neural networks or when a bounded range is required.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why tree models do not require scaling:** Decision trees split on thresholds (e.g., \"study_hours > 4.2\"). The split threshold is invariant to linear transformations. Multiplying all values by 100 shifts the threshold but not the tree's logic.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if scaling is skipped:** In linear regression, the coefficient for attendance_percentage (range 0–100) will be ~10× smaller than the coefficient for study_hours (range 0–10), making comparison of feature importance via coefficients misleading. In gradient descent, training may not converge within a reasonable number of iterations."
   ]
