   "source": [
    "### 7.1 Univariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Univariate analysis examines each variable in isolation to understand its distribution, central tendency, and spread.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mean:** The arithmetic average. Sensitive to extreme values.  \n",
    "**Median:** The middle value when sorted. Robust to outliers.  \n",
    "**Mode:** The most frequently occurring value. Used for categorical variables.  \n",
    "**Variance (σ²):** The average squared deviation from the mean. Large variance = high spread.  \n",
    "**Standard Deviation (σ):** Square root of variance; expressed in the same units as the variable.  \n",
    "**Skewness:** Measures asymmetry. Positive skew: long right tail; negative skew: long left tail. A normal distribution has skewness = 0.  \n",
    "**Kurtosis:** Measures tail \"heaviness\". Normal distribution has kurtosis = 3 (excess kurtosis = 0). High kurtosis = more extreme outliers than expected.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Distribution shapes:**  \n",
    "- *Symmetric/normal* — bell curve, mean ≈ median ≈ mode.  \n",
    "- *Right-skewed* — most values clustered at lower end; mean > median.  \n",
    "- *Left-skewed* — most values clustered at higher end; mean < median.  \n",
    "- *Bimodal* — two peaks; may indicate two distinct sub-populations."
   ]
