    "### 7.2 Bivariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Bivariate analysis examines the relationship between two variables simultaneously.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Correlation coefficient (Pearson's r):**  \n",
    "`r = Σ[(xᵢ − x̄)(yᵢ − ȳ)] / [n·σₓ·σᵧ]`\n",
    "\n",
    "- r ∈ [−1, 1]  \n",
    "- r = +1: perfect positive linear relationship  \n",
    "- r = −1: perfect negative linear relationship  \n",
    "- r = 0: no *linear* relationship (non-linear relationships may still exist)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Positive vs negative correlation:**  \n",
    "- *Positive* — as X increases, Y tends to increase (study hours vs exam score).  \n",
    "- *Negative* — as X increases, Y tends to decrease (social media hours vs exam score).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Correlation vs causation:** Correlation measures association, not causation. Two variables may co-vary because a third variable (a *confounder*) influences both. For example, students with more parental support may both study more *and* eat better — creating a correlation between study hours and diet quality that is not causal.\n",
    "\n",
    "**P-values:** A p-value is the probability of observing a correlation at least as extreme as the computed one, assuming the null hypothesis (r = 0) is true. If p < 0.05, the correlation is deemed statistically significant at the 5% level."
   ]
  },
