    "### 7.3 Multivariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**Multicollinearity:** Occurs when two or more predictor variables are highly correlated. In linear regression, multicollinear predictors cause unstable coefficient estimates — small changes in data produce large swings in coefficients. The model cannot reliably attribute variance to one predictor versus another.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Variance Inflation Factor (VIF):** Quantifies how much the variance of a regression coefficient is inflated due to multicollinearity. `VIF = 1 / (1 − R²ⱼ)` where R²ⱼ is obtained by regressing predictor j against all other predictors.  \n",
    "- VIF = 1: no multicollinearity.  \n",
    "- VIF 1–5: moderate; generally acceptable.  \n",
    "- VIF > 10: severe multicollinearity; consider removing or combining features.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Impact of correlated predictors:** Inflated standard errors, incorrect p-values, and unreliable feature importance rankings in linear models. Tree-based models are less affected because they select the best split at each node independently."
   ]
  },
